definition.value: An organic phosphate that is phosphoric acid in which one of the hydrogens is replaced by an organyl group.
A polyether antibiotic that is isolated from cultures of a strain of Streptomyces albus.
An EC 3.5.1.* (non-peptide linear amide C-N hydrolase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of amidase (EC 3.5.1.4).

A member of the class of benzoxaboroles that is 1,3-dihydro-1-hydroxy-2,1-benzoxaborole substituted at position 5 by a fluoro group. A topical antifungal agent used for the treatment of onychomycosis (fungal infection of the toenails and fingernails).

An oxonium betaine obtained by deprotonation of the 7-hydroxy group of anthocyanidin 3-glucoside 5-[(6-O-4-hydroxycinnamoyl)glucoside]. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).

An oxonium betaine obtained by deprotonation of the 7-hydroxy group of any anthocyanidin 5-O-beta-D-glucoside 3-O-beta-D-sambubioside. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
An oxonium betaine obtained by deprotonation of the 5-hydroxy group of any anthocyanidin 3-O-beta-D-sambubioside. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
An oxonium betaine obtained by deprotonation of the 5-hydroxy group of any anthocyanidin 3-O-sophoroside. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
A phenolate anion obtained by deprotonation of the 2-hydroxy group of (S)-versiconol. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).

A phenolate anion obtained by deprotonation of the hydroxy group located at the position ortho to the carbonyl group of isoliquiritigenin. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
A polyunsaturated fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of 9-HOTrE, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A phenolate anion obtained by deprotonation of the 8-hydroxy group of (2S-3S)-versiconal hemiacetal. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
A phenolate anion obtained by deprotonation of the 8-hydroxy group of versicolorin B. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
A D-glucosyl-N-acylsphingosine in which the ceramide N-acyl group is specified as hexanoyl.
An EC 6.1.1.* (ligases forming aminoacyl tRNA and related compounds) inhibitor that inhibits the action of leucine--tRNA synthetase (EC 6.1.1.4).
A member of the class of monomethoxyflavones that is 3'-methoxyflavone bearing an additional amino substituent at position 2'.
A sphingolipid that is the N-dodecanoyl (lauroyl) derivative of L-erythro-sphingosine.
A cationic sphingoid resulting from the protonation of the amino group of L-erythro-sphingosine; major species at pH 7.3.
A phenylalanine derivative that is L-phenylalanine in which the hydrogen at position 3 on the benzene ring is replaced by a fluoro group.

A disaccharide derivative consisting of two 3-deoxy-alpha-D-manno-oct-2-ulopyranonosyl units joined via an alpha-(2->8)-linkage with an O-allyl group at the anomeric centre and with the carboxy group of the residue at the non-reducing end methyl-esterified.
The carbohydrate acid derivative anion formed by proton loss from the free carboxy group of alpha-Kdo1Me-(2->8)-alpha-Kdo-OAll
A food additive that is used to make or keep fruit or vegetable tissues firm and crisp. or which interacts with gelling agents such as pectin to produce or strengthen a gel.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol 3-diphosphate in which both of the phosphatidyl acyl groups are specified as octanoyl.
An antioxidant that used as a food additives to help guard against food deterioration.
A food preservative that acts by chelating with metal cations (particularly those of copper, iron and nickel) that catalyse the oxidation of fats in food.
A substance added to powdered or granulated materials in order to prevent the formation of lumps and so facilitate its packaging or transport.
An anticaking agent that is used to reduced the tendency of particles of food to adhere to one another.
A food additive that is used to preserve the structure of food.
An organic chloride salt having dibenziodolium as the counterion.
A compound that is used to keep a substance moist.
A humectant that is used as a food additive to prevent foodstuffs from drying out.
A food additive that is used to increase the viscosity of foodstuffs.
A food additive which liberates gas so as to increase the volume of a dough or batter, resulting in a lighter and softer finished product.
A food additive that is applied to the external surface or a food in order to give a smooth shiny appearance  and/or to provide a protective coating to foodstuffs.
A substance that reduces and hinders the formation of foam in solutions and other liquids during their industrial or laboratory processing.

A food additive that is a (generally inert) gas which is used to envelop foodstuffs during packing and so protect them from unwanted chemical reactions such as food spoilage or oxidation during subsequent transport and storage. The term includes propellant gases, used to expel foods from a container.
A phenolate anion obtained by deprotonation of the 8-hydroxy group of (2S-3S)-versiconal hemiacetal acetate. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
A phenolate anion obtained by deprotonation of the 8-hydroxy group of versicolorin A. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
A phenolate anion obtained by deprotonation of the 7-hydroxy group of noreugenin. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).

A phenolate anion obtained by deprotonation of one of the two ortho-hydroxy groups of 2',4,4',6'-tetrahydroxychalcone 4'-O-beta-D-glucoside. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
A zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the 5-hydroxy to the tertiary amino group of aclacinomycin T. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).

A cyclohexenecarboxylate ester that is the ethyl ester of oseltamivir acid. An antiviral prodrug (it is hydrolysed to the active free carboxylic acid in the liver), it is used to slow the spread of influenza.
A zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the 5-hydroxy to the tertiary amino group of aclacinomycin A. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
A peptide anion that is the conjugate base of vancomycin aglycone and the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
A hydroxy monocarboxylic acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy and 7-hydroxy groups of tetracenomycin F2. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).

An organophosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of all but one of the phosphate and diphosphate OH groups of 1,5-bis(diphospho)-1D-myo-inositol 2,3,4,6-tetrakisphosphate. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
A flavonoid oxoanion that is a tetraanionic form of quercetin 3,3',7-trissulfate. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
A zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the 5-hydroxy to the tertiary amino group of aclacinomycin Y. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
